<dl id="n32071e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n32" href="#n32071e">N32 (VI.B.23)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n32all.htm#n32071e"> 71(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> garlandmade / basket / basket of the garland</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The genitive postpositions have an interesting origin. In Buddhist Sanskrit the words <i>krtas</i>, done, and <i>krtyas</i>, to be done, were added to a noun to form a kind of genitive. A synonym of <i>krtyas</i> was <i>karyas</i>. These three words were all adjectives, and agreed with the thing possessed in gender, number, and case; thus, <i>mala-krte karande</i>, in <mark>the basket of the garland, literally, in the garland-made basket</mark>. <small> &ldquo;HINDOSTANI&rdquo; <a name="EBHI" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EBHI"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 482(a) [Grammar]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
